@page "/readme"
@rendermode InteractiveServer

<PageTitle>ReadMe</PageTitle>

<h1>ReadMe</h1>
<p class="readme-subtitle">A walkthrough of the key files in this Blazor application.</p>

<div class="file-section">
    <div class="file-header">
        <span class="file-icon">📄</span>
        <h2>Home.razor</h2>
        <span class="file-path">Components/Pages/Home.razor</span>
    </div>
    <div class="file-body">
        <p>The main page of the application, responsible for uploading, validating, and analysing HTTP access log files.</p>

        <h3>File Upload</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>
                Provides a <strong>drag-and-drop zone</strong> and a <strong>"Browse Files" button</strong> for selecting
                <code>.log</code> files up to 10 MB.
            </li>
            <li>
                Two <code>InputFile</code> components are used: a transparent overlay covering the entire drop area
                for drag-and-drop, and a hidden one inside the button for the file picker dialog. Both fire the
                same <code>HandleFileUpload</code> handler.
            </li>
            <li>
                The <code>@@ondragenter</code>, <code>@@ondragleave</code>, and <code>@@ondragover</code> events
                toggle a <code>drag-over</code> CSS class for visual feedback when a file is dragged over the area.
            </li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Format Guide</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>
                Displays a colour-coded visual breakdown of the expected <em>Combined Log Format</em> so users
                know the exact structure their log file should follow before uploading.
            </li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Validation &amp; Feedback</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>
                After a file is selected, its content is read into a <code>MemoryStream</code> and passed to
                <code>LogFileService.Validate()</code>.
            </li>
            <li>
                If validation <strong>fails</strong>, an error banner is shown with the file name and up to 5 offending
                lines (each truncated to 80 characters). If there are more than 5 invalid lines, a summary count is appended.
            </li>
            <li>
                If validation <strong>passes</strong>, a success message is displayed with the file name and size.
            </li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Log File Analysis</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>
                After a successful upload, <code>LogFileService.InterrogateLogFile()</code> is called to analyse the log content.
            </li>
            <li>
                The results are displayed in a card-based grid layout showing:
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Unique IP Addresses</strong> — A highlighted card with the total count.</li>
                    <li><strong>Top 3 Most Visited URLs</strong> — An ordered list with visit counts displayed in badges.</li>
                    <li><strong>Top 3 Most Active IP Addresses</strong> — An ordered list with request counts displayed in badges.</li>
                </ul>
            </li>
            <li>
                Previous analysis results are cleared (<code>interrogationResult = null</code>) at the start of each
                new upload to prevent stale data from being shown.
            </li>
        </ul>

    </div>
</div>

<div class="file-section">
    <div class="file-header">
        <span class="file-icon">🔧</span>
        <h2>LogFileService.cs</h2>
        <span class="file-path">Services/LogFileService.cs</span>
    </div>
    <div class="file-body">
        <p>
            A scoped service that handles log file validation and analysis, keeping business logic out of the Razor component.
            Implements the <code>ILogFileService</code> interface to support dependency injection and unit testing.
        </p>

        <h3>ILogFileService Interface</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>Defined in <code>Services/ILogFileService.cs</code> with two methods: <code>Validate()</code> and <code>InterrogateLogFile()</code>.</li>
            <li>Allows <code>Home.razor</code> to depend on an abstraction (<code>@@inject ILogFileService</code>) rather than the concrete class, enabling mocking in unit tests.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Regex Patterns</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>
                <strong>CombinedLogFormatRegex</strong> — Validates that a line matches the Combined Log Format structure.
                Used by <code>Validate()</code>.
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong>LogEntryParserRegex</strong> — Extracts the <em>IP address</em> (group 1) and the <em>URL</em>
                (group 2) from a log line. Used by <code>InterrogateLogFile()</code>.
            </li>
            <li>
                Both use <code>[GeneratedRegex]</code> — the .NET source-generated regex approach — which is more
                performant than <code>new Regex(..., RegexOptions.Compiled)</code> and is the recommended pattern
                for .NET 9.
            </li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Validate(string content)</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>Splits the file content into lines and tests each non-empty line against <code>CombinedLogFormatRegex</code>.</li>
            <li>Returns a <code>LogValidationResult</code> indicating success (with a line count) or failure (with a list of invalid lines or an error message).</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>InterrogateLogFile(string content)</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>Parses each line with <code>LogEntryParserRegex</code> to extract the IP address and URL.</li>
            <li>Tallies occurrences in two dictionaries using case-insensitive comparison.</li>
            <li>
                Returns a <code>LogInterrogationResult</code> containing:
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>UniqueIpAddressCount</strong> — The number of distinct IP addresses.</li>
                    <li><strong>TopVisitedUrls</strong> — The top 3 URLs ranked by visit count.</li>
                    <li><strong>TopActiveIpAddresses</strong> — The top 3 IP addresses ranked by request count.</li>
                </ul>
            </li>
        </ul>

    </div>
</div>

<div class="file-section">
    <div class="file-header">
        <span class="file-icon">⚙️</span>
        <h2>Program.cs</h2>
        <span class="file-path">Program.cs</span>
    </div>
    <div class="file-body">
        <p>The application entry point that configures services and the HTTP request pipeline.</p>

        <h3>Service Registration</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>
                <strong>AddRazorComponents / AddInteractiveServerComponents</strong> — Registers the services
                required for Blazor component rendering and enables the Interactive Server render mode
                (SignalR-based).
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong>AddScoped&lt;ILogFileService, LogFileService&gt;</strong> — Registers the log file service
                against its <code>ILogFileService</code> interface with a <em>scoped</em> lifetime (one instance per
                SignalR circuit / user session). Using an interface enables dependency injection and mocking in unit tests.
            </li>
        </ul>

    </div>
</div>

